<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,429,775]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,429,455]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Tube white, smooth, with three longitudinal ridges, lacks crests, peristomes or alveoli. Opercular peduncle smooth, white. Operculum with fleshy, bulbous part and distal cap forming several (4–6) discoidal plates, jointed by central column (
<figureCitation box="[554,664,509,535]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="43.[151,255,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[268,1321,198,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-135@43.[265,1325,194,1770]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 10. A–D: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Baja California Sur, UMAR-Poly 107. A–B, operculum, lateral and aboral views. C: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Oaxaca, UMAR-Poly 93. C, operculum, lateral view. D: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Guerrero, UMAR-Poly 108. D, operculum, lateral view. E: Rhodopsis pusilla, from Bermuda, USNM 118145, neotype. E, operculum, lateral view. F–G: Salmacina chilensis, from Chile. F–G, collar chaetae, lateral view and detail. H–J: Salmacina tribranchiata, from Sinaloa. H, anterior part, dorsal view. I, collar chaeta. J, “Apomatus” chaeta. K: Semivermilia pomatostegoides, from Tripoli (Mediterranean). K, operculum, lateral view. (Fig. E, redrawn from Ben-Eliahu &amp; ten Hove, 1989. Figs F–G, redrawn from Gallardo, 1969. Fig. K, redrawn from Zibrowius, 1969)." pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 10K</figureCitation>
). Thoracic membrane short, extends to second thoracic chaetiger. Collar with hooded (limbate) chaetae, with bundles of few chaetae. Thorax with “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benedict" authorityYear="1887" box="[1129,1255,549,575]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Apomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Apomatus</taxonomicName>
” chaetae. Thoracic uncini saw- to rasp-shaped, with gouged anterior tooth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1436,429,775]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,301,629,655]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Habitat.</emphasis>
Depth: Sublittoral 
<quantity box="[544,653,629,655]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" unit="m" value="17.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="15.0">15–20 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bailey-Brock, J. H." box="[673,909,629,655]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="213 - 453" refId="ref32901" refString="Bailey-Brock, J. H. (1987) Phylum Annelida. pp. 213 - 453 In: Devaney, D. M. &amp; Eldredge, L. G. (eds), Reef and shore fauna of Hawaii. Section 3: Sipuncula through Annelida. Special Publication of the Bernice P. Bishop Museum, 64, 453 pp." type="book chapter" year="1987">Bailey-Brock 1987</bibRefCitation>
); originally recorded to 
<quantity box="[1213,1293,629,655]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" unit="m" value="140.0">140 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zibrowius, H." pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="1 - 22" refId="ref38056" refString="Zibrowius, H. (1969) Review of some little known genera of Serpulidae (Annelida: Polychaeta). Smithsonian Contribution to Zoology, 42, 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="1969">Zibrowius 1969</bibRefCitation>
). On coral rubble and calcareous algae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
